{
  "texts": [
    "• Relational, related to how people see AI and to the resulting psychological and metaphysical human-AI relationship foot_0; • Societal, related to the social and economic costs and consequences of the development and use of AI.",
    "Importantly, the distinction between these levels is mainly for the sake of analysis: in practice the same factor may appear on different levels, for instance in terms of its \"proximal\" and \"distal\" effects.",
    "To illustrate, brain-inspired AI may have the proximal positive effect of needing less energy which may lead to the distal effect of cheaper systems and a conse-quent more democratic access to it.",
    "More specifically, neuromorphic architectures can benefit from reduced power consumption compared to their more conventional counterparts, if they inherit relevant aspects of brain structure and dynamics.",
    "For example, the characteristic in-memory computing aspect of brain networks directly circumvents the notorious von-Neumann bottleneck (Indiveri and Liu 2015)."
  ]
}